sec.p:
Curcumin, a naturally occurring polyphenol derived from the rhizome of the turmeric plant (
Curcuma longa
), is one such compound. It has been used for centuries in traditional medicine and is renowned for its potent anti‐inflammatory, antioxidant, and antimicrobial properties (El‐Saadony et al. 2023). A growing body of preclinical evidence suggests that curcumin and its formulations can improve glycemic control through multiple mechanisms. These include enhancing insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues, preserving pancreatic β‐cell function, reducing hepatic gluconeogenesis, and ameliorating chronic inflammation and oxidative stress, which are key pathophysiological features of insulin resistance and T2D (Bhatti et al. 2022; Liu et al. 2025; Marton, Pescinini‐e‐Salzedas, et al. 2021; Marton, Pescinini, et al. 2021).
